{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5c43052-5ef9-4e4f-8e67-51f4a82745b4","content":"The standard approach in .NET is to use **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — a well-established library that wraps `System.IO` types behind interfaces.\n\n**Steps:**\n\n1. **Install the NuGet package:**\n   ```\n   dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\n   ```\n\n2. **Inject `IFileSystem` instead of using static `File`/`Directory` calls:**\n   ```csharp\n   public class MyService\n   {\n       private readonly IFileSystem _fs;\n       public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;\n\n       public void Save(string path, string content)\n           => _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n   }\n   ```\n\n3. **In production**, register the real implementation:\n   ```csharp\n   services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();\n   ```\n\n4. **In tests**, use the companion mock package:\n   ```\n   dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n   ```\n   ```csharp\n   var fs = new MockFileSystem();\n   var svc = new MyService(fs);\n   svc.Save(\"/tmp/out.txt\", \"hello\");\n   Assert.Equal(\"hello\", fs.File.ReadAllText(\"/tmp/out.txt\"));\n   ```\n\nThe API surface mirrors `System.IO` almost 1:1 (`IFile`, `IDirectory`, `IPath`, etc.), so the migration is mostly mechanical — replace `File.` with `_fs.File.` and `Directory.` with `_fs.Directory.`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4eb76300-fd20-4ec1-ac14-3f0464a5e78f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in .NET. This is a general software engineering question about best practices, not a task requiring code changes. Let me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":438,"requestId":"A042:10A559:1B0C285:1EB1B59:69FE94FA"},"id":"de7cb3f6-acc9-4a1e-9a06-59956e53e5e3","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:59:31.744Z","parentId":"b4707067-ef05-4495-900b-db56684bc6ab"}
